  "prompt": "What are proportional taxes?",
  "response": "Proportional taxes, also known as flat taxes, are a type of tax system where the tax rate is consistent regardless of the taxpayer's income level or wealth. This means every individual or entity is taxed at the same percentage rate. Unlike progressive taxes, which increase the tax rate as income increases, or regressive taxes, which take a larger percentage from lower-income earners, proportional taxes apply the same rate across the board. \n\nFor example, if there is a proportional tax rate of 10%, someone earning $30,000 a year would pay $3,000 in taxes, and someone earning $100,000 would pay $10,000. This type of tax system is often advocated for its simplicity and perceived fairness, as it treats all taxpayers equally in terms of the rate they pay. However, it can also be criticized for not taking into account the varying abilities of individuals to pay, potentially placing a heavier burden on lower-income earners.",
